const SP_DICT={
            'limpet':['Limpet <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Cone-shaped snails that clamp down incredibly hard onto rocks to trap moisture and resist wave action.','Algae scraped from rocks.','Oystercatchers, starfish, crabs.',['Teeth are made of goethite (the strongest known biological material).','Return to the exact same home scar on a rock every day.','Can live for over 10 years in the wild.']],
            'sculpin':['Tidepool Sculpin <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Small, camouflaged fish that can survive in warm, oxygen-poor tidepools during low tide.','Small invertebrates, amphipods, worms.','Larger fish, coastal birds.',['Can breathe air briefly if stranded.','Camouflages perfectly with tidepool rocks by changing its coloration slightly.','Can quickly dart and freeze to avoid detection by predators.']],
            'crab':['Shore Crab <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Crabs have tough exoskeletons to prevent water loss. They wedge deeply into damp crevices.','Scavenger (dead fish, algae, detritus).','Birds, octopuses, larger crabs.',['Walk sideways due to the articulation of their leg joints.','Can regenerate lost limbs over successive molts.','Have a complex social hierarchy based heavily on claw size.']],
            'barnacle':['Acorn Barnacle <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','They glue their heads to rocks! Close plates to trap seawater inside.','Plankton and detritus (filter feeder).','Whelks, starfish, some fish.',['They are crustaceans, making them closer relatives to crabs than to snails.','Have the longest penis relative to body size of any animal.','Secrete a cement that is among the most powerful natural glues known to science.']],
            'starfish':['Ochre Sea Star <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Uses a unique water vascular system and tube feet to powerfully grip rocks.','Mussels, clams, oysters.','Sea otters, seagulls, other starfish.',['Pushes its stomach out of its mouth to digest prey externally.','Can regenerate its entire body from a single severed arm (if part of the central disc remains).','Has absolutely no brain or blood.']],
            'anemone':['Sea Anemone <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Retracts its tentacles and closes up into a tight, water-filled blob to survive desiccation.','Small fish, plankton, shrimp.','Sea slugs (nudibranchs), sea turtles.',['They are carnivorous animals, not plants.','Closely related to jellyfish and corals.','Can clone themselves by literally tearing their bodies in half.']],
            'otter':['Sea Otter','','A keystone marine mammal that uses tools to crack open sea urchins, keeping kelp forests healthy.','Sea urchins, crabs, clams, mussels.','Great white sharks, killer whales.',['Have the densest fur in the animal kingdom (up to 1 million hairs per square inch).','Use rocks as anvils on their chests to break open hard shells.','Hold hands while sleeping in the water to avoid drifting apart.']],
            'phytoplankton':['Phytoplankton','','Microscopic algae that form the base of the marine food web and produce half of the oxygen on Earth.','Photosynthesis (sunlight and nutrients).','Zooplankton, small fish, filter-feeding whales.',['Produce 50% of the world’s oxygen.','Responsible for the marine "snow" that eventually feeds the deep sea.','Form the foundational base of almost all marine food webs.']],
            'coral':['Reef-Building Coral <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Form massive calcium carbonate structures and host symbiotic zooxanthellae algae for energy.','Photosynthetic byproducts from zooxanthellae, microscopic plankton.','Parrotfish, crown-of-thorns starfish.',['Coral reefs support roughly 25% of all marine life.','A single coral branch is actually a colony of thousands of tiny animals called polyps.','They expel their symbiotic algae (coral bleaching) when stressed by warming temperatures.']],
            'kelp':['Giant Kelp <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Fast-growing macroalgae that creates dense underwater forests supporting huge biodiversity.','Photosynthesis (sunlight and nutrients).','Sea urchins, kelp crabs.',['Can grow up to 2 feet in a single day under ideal conditions.','Forms massive underwater forests that buffer coastlines from storm waves.','Extracts iodine from seawater, concentrating it up to 100,000 times the ocean level.']],
            'clownfish':['Clownfish','','Lives symbiotically among the stinging tentacles of sea anemones on shallow coral reefs.','Algae, zooplankton, leftover anemone meals.','Larger reef fish, reef sharks.',['All are born male; the largest, most dominant fish in a group becomes female.','Develop immunity to anemone stings by constantly rubbing a protective mucus on their bodies.','Communicate by making distinct popping and clicking noises.']],
            'parrotfish':['Parrotfish','','Uses its beak-like teeth to scrape algae off coral, excreting fine white sand.','Algae growing on coral reefs.','Moray eels, reef sharks.',['Excrete fine white sand after digesting coral rocks (creating many tropical beaches).','Sleep in a protective mucus cocoon at night to hide their scent from predators.','Their teeth constantly grow to replace the wear from scraping hard rocks.']],
            'sunfish':['Ocean Sunfish','','The heaviest bony fish in the world, often seen basking at the surface to warm up after deep dives.','Jellyfish, zooplankton, small fish.','Sea lions, killer whales, large sharks.',['Can lay up to 300 million eggs at once, more than any other vertebrate.','Lacks a true tail fin, using a scalloped pseudo-tail called a "clavus" to steer.','Often get infested with skin parasites, which birds and small fish pick off while they bask.']],
            'mahimahi':['Mahi-Mahi','','A fast, surface-dwelling predator known for its brilliant colors and blunt forehead.','Flying fish, squid, crabs.','Marlin, sailfish, large tuna.',['Grow incredibly fast, reaching up to 3 feet in length in a single year.','Mature males have prominent, blunt, square foreheads.','Flash bright neon blue and green colors when excited or actively hunting.']],
            'tuna':['Bluefin Tuna','','A master of the Epipelagic! Fusiform body shape and strongly countershaded.','Smaller fish (mackerel, herring), squid.','Killer whales, great white sharks.',['Warm-blooded, allowing them to swim quickly in extremely cold waters.','Must swim constantly with their mouths open to breathe (ram ventilation).','Can reach burst speeds of up to 43 mph.']],
            'shark':['Great White Shark','','Apex predator relying on keen eyesight, electroreception, and immense burst speed.','Seals, sea lions, large fish.','Killer whales (rarely).',['Can detect one drop of blood in 100 liters of water.','Have a special sensory organ (Ampullae of Lorenzini) to detect the electric fields of prey.','Roll their eyes completely backward into their head to protect them when striking.']],
            'turtle':['Sea Turtle','','Pelagic cruiser. Streamlined shell reduces drag, uses internal counter-current heat exchange.','Jellyfish, sponges, seagrass.','Tiger sharks, killer whales.',['Unlike land turtles, they cannot retract their heads or flippers into their shells.','Females return to the exact beach they were born to lay their own eggs.','Have special salt glands near their eyes to excrete excess ocean salt, making them look like they are crying.']],
            'manta':['Manta Ray','','A gentle giant! Uses large cephalic fins to funnel plankton-rich water into its mouth.','Zooplankton, small fish.','Large sharks, killer whales.',['Have the largest brain-to-body ratio of any fish.','Are one of the few fish that can recognize themselves in a mirror, indicating self-awareness.','The spot patterns on their bellies are completely unique to each individual, like fingerprints.']],
            'swordfish':['Swordfish','','Fast predators that migrate into the twilight zone during the day to hunt, using special organs to heat their eyes.','Squid, pelagic fish.','Mako sharks, killer whales.',['Have a specialized heating organ near their eyes to keep their brain warm and improve vision in deep, cold water.','Do not actually spear prey with their sword, but use it to rapidly slash and stun them.','Lose all their teeth and scales as they grow into adults.']],
            'ctenophore':['Comb Jelly','','Translucent predators found across almost all ocean zones, from sunlit surfaces down to the deep abyss.','Copepods, small larvae.','Sea turtles, various fish, other ctenophores.',['Do not sting; instead, they use sticky cells called colloblasts to capture prey.','Represent one of the oldest known animal lineages on Earth.','While featured in the Twilight Zone here, they live at virtually every depth.']],
            'lanternfish':['Lanternfish','','Uses bioluminescent photophores on its belly to counter-illuminate.','Zooplankton, small crustaceans.','Tuna, squid, penguins, dolphins.',['Make up a huge portion of global fish biomass (up to 65% of all deep-sea fish).','Perform the largest daily mass animal migration on Earth, rising to the surface at night.','Different species have unique arrangements of light organs to identify each other in the dark.']],
            'squid':['Vampire Squid','','Not a true squid! Turns inside out like a spiky umbrella when threatened in the Twilight Zone.','Marine snow (dead plankton, fecal matter, detritus).','Deep-diving whales, large fish.',['The only cephalopod known to not eat live prey (it is a detritivore).','Has the largest eyes relative to body size of any animal in the world.','Does not ink; instead, it ejects glowing bioluminescent mucus to confuse predators.']],
            'hatchetfish':['Hatchetfish','','Coin-thin body and tubular eyes pointing straight up to spot silhouettes.','Copepods, small crustaceans.','Viperfish, lanternfish, larger predators.',['Extremely flat, resembling a silver coin or a hatchet blade.','Eyes point strictly upward to spot silhouettes of prey against the faint surface light.','Belly has light organs perfectly matching the downwelling sunlight to erase their shadow (counter-illumination).']],
            'bristlemouth':['Bristlemouth','','Thought to be the most abundant vertebrate genus on Earth!','Tiny crustaceans, copepods.','Dragonfish, larger squid.',['Believed to be the most numerous vertebrate genus on the planet (numbering in the trillions).','Incredibly tiny, usually measuring less than 3 inches long.','Can unhinge their jaws to eat prey nearly their own size.']],
            'dragonfish':['Deep Sea Dragonfish','','Fierce predators with oversized jaws and a bioluminescent barbel attached to their chin to lure prey.','Small fish, lanternfish.','Larger deep-sea fish.',['Has black stomach tissue to hide the glowing light of swallowed bioluminescent prey.','Their massive teeth are transparent so prey cannot see them coming.','Produces a red bioluminescence to hunt, a color invisible to almost all other deep-sea creatures.']],
            'snipeeel':['Snipe Eel','','Slender fish with curving, beak-like jaws that range widely across both the Mesopelagic and Bathypelagic zones.','Small shrimp, tiny crustaceans.','Deep-sea sharks, larger fish.',['Swims backwards while trailing its jaws open to snag the antennae of deep-sea shrimp.','Has more vertebrae than almost any other animal (up to 750).','Their depth range spans from 300m down to over 4,000m.']],
            'anglerfish':['Humpback Anglerfish','','Uses a glowing esca (lure) filled with symbiotic bioluminescent bacteria to attract prey.','Fish, crustaceans.','Rarely preyed upon due to depth and isolation.',['Males are tiny parasites that bite the female and permanently fuse into her bloodstream.','The glowing lure on the female’s head is filled with symbiotic glowing bacteria.','Can consume prey twice their own size due to a highly expandable stomach.']],
            'gulper':['Gulper Eel','','Massive, loosely-hinged jaws to swallow prey much larger than itself.','Small fish, squid, occasional large prey.','Deep-sea sharks, lancetfish.',['The tip of its tail has a tiny glowing organ to attract prey or potential mates in the dark.','Its skull is incredibly tiny compared to its massive, pelican-like jaw.','Lacks a swim bladder, scales, and pelvic fins entirely.']],
            'vampire':['Vampire Squid','','A peaceful detritivore that spans both the Mesopelagic and Bathypelagic zones, often resting in the Oxygen Minimum Zone.','Marine snow (dead plankton, fecal matter).','Sperm whales, deep-diving sharks.',['Capable of slowing its metabolism to incredibly low rates to survive in the OMZ.','"Cloak" is made of webbed arms covered in fleshy, non-stinging spines called cirri.','Uses two extremely long, sticky filaments to gather falling debris like a net.']],
            'dumbo':['Dumbo Octopus <span class="tag-benthopelagic">Benthopelagic</span>','','Flaps ear-like fins to hover. Completely lacks an ink sac.','Polychaete worms, bivalves, crustaceans.','Deep-sea sharks, other cephalopods.',['The deepest-living octopus known to science.','Swims by flapping its ear-like fins rather than using jet propulsion like shallow-water octopuses.','Swallows its prey whole instead of tearing it with a beak.']],
            'seaspider':['Sea Spider <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Benthic marine arthropods with incredibly long legs; their bodies are so small that organs are located in their legs!','Anemones, sponges (sucks their juices).','Deep-sea crabs.',['Breathes directly by diffusion through the surface of its legs.','Male sea spiders are the ones who carry the eggs until they hatch.','Digestion and reproduction occur inside their legs due to their incredibly tiny central body cavity.']],
            'basketstar':['Basket Star <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','A complex benthic brittle star mostly found on the seafloor at bathyal depths, though some species reach down into the Abyssal zone.','Zooplankton, marine snow.','Bottom-dwelling fish, crabs.',['Can fully regenerate their incredibly complex, branching arms if damaged.','Uses microscopic hooks on its arms to snare prey passing by in the dark.','Curls up into a tight, knotted ball when disturbed to protect its vulnerable central disk.']],
            'cucumber':['Sea Cucumber <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','A benthic vacuum cleaner! Crawls along the abyssal mud eating organic marine snow.','Detritus, organic matter sifted from mud.','Deep-sea fish, crabs.',['Breathe through their anus using internal respiratory trees.','Can expel their internal organs out of their body to distract predators, and then fully regenerate them.','Make up the vast majority of the biological mass on the deep ocean floor.']],
            'tripod':['Tripod Fish <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','A benthic fish that uses elongated fin rays to stand like a tripod above the soft mud to sense vibrations.','Small crustaceans drifting in currents.','Larger bottom-dwelling fish.',['Essentially "blind," relying entirely on vibration-sensing pectoral fins to find food.','Hermaphroditic; can actually fertilize its own eggs if it cannot find a mate in the deep ocean.','"Stands" perfectly still facing the current to effortlessly catch floating prey.']],
            'isopod':['Giant Isopod <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','Benthic scavengers exhibiting Abyssal Gigantism! Extreme cold delays maturity, allowing them to grow massive in the bathyal zone.','Carrion (whale falls, dead fish).','Deep-sea sharks, octopuses.',['Can survive for up to 5 years without eating a single meal.','Have four sets of powerful jaws to tear apart dead animals that fall from above.','Can roll themselves into a tight, armored ball when threatened by predators.']],
            'rattail':['Rattail Fish <span class="tag-benthopelagic">Benthopelagic</span>','','Benthic and demersal scavengers mostly found in the bathyal zone, with a massive head containing highly sensitive lateral lines.','Crustaceans, small fish, carrion.','Deep-sea sharks.',['Also known as "grenadiers," they have extremely sensitive snouts to smell food buried deep in the mud.','Emit drumming sounds using muscles attached to their swim bladder.','Extremely slow-growing and can live for over 70 years.']],
            'seapig':['Sea Pig <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','A specialized, benthic sea cucumber that walks on the muddy abyssal plain using enlarged tube feet.','Organic detritus found in deep-sea mud.','Deep-sea crabs, larger scavengers.',['A type of sea cucumber that actually "walks" using water-inflated legs.','Often found in massive herds, all facing the exact same direction into the current.','Have "antennae" on their heads which are actually modified legs used to sense food in the mud.']],
            'foraminifera':['Foraminifera <span class="tag-multi">Benthic & Planktonic</span>','','Single-celled protists that construct complex shells; they thrive in extreme trench pressures.','Dissolved organic matter, bacteria.','Deep-sea snails, small crustaceans.',['Single-celled organisms that manage to build complex, incredibly beautiful shells.','Shells in the hadal zone are made of organic material or glued sand, as regular calcium shells dissolve at high pressure.','Their ancient fossils are heavily used by scientists to reconstruct prehistoric ocean temperatures.']],
            'snailfish':['Mariana Snailfish <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','The deepest known fish! Has a gelatinous body and massive amounts of TMAO.','Small amphipods and crustaceans.','Larger amphipods, rarely other deep-sea fish.',['Current record holder for the deepest living fish ever discovered by humans.','Have soft, translucent bodies with almost completely uncalcified bones to survive the pressure.','Lay incredibly large eggs (up to 1cm in diameter) for a fish of their size.']],
            'tubeworm':['Riftia Tubeworm <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','A purely benthic creature that lacks a mouth and stomach! Houses chemosynthetic bacteria in its trophosome organ near bathyal hydrothermal vents.','Energy produced internally by symbiotic chemosynthetic bacteria.','Vent crabs, blind shrimp.',['The fastest-growing marine invertebrates known to science.','Their bright red plumes are filled with hemoglobin to transport toxic hydrogen sulfide to their bacteria.','Thrive in water temperatures bordering on boiling, right next to hydrothermal vents.']],
            'amphipod':['Supergiant Amphipod <span class="tag-benthic">Benthic</span>','','A trench scavenger! Uses specialized aluminum shields and TMAO to survive.','Carrion (dead animals sinking into the trench).','Snailfish.',['Extract aluminum from the deep-sea mud to build a protective pressure shield around their bodies.','Contain special enzymes that allow them to break down and eat wood that falls into the ocean trenches.','Can grow up to 10 times larger than their shallow-water amphipod relatives.']],
            'cuskeel':['Cusk Eel <span class="tag-benthopelagic">Benthopelagic</span>','','Specifically the species Abyssobrotula galatheae, an iconic hadal dweller that held the record for deepest fish for decades.','Small invertebrates, amphipods.','Larger deep-sea scavengers.',['This specific species was collected at an astonishing depth of 8,370 meters (27,460 feet) in the Puerto Rico Trench.','Have pelvic fins modified into feeler-like barbels under their chin to sense the muddy bottom.','Possess extremely small eyes, as sight is completely useless in the pitch-black trench.']],
            'swimcucumber':['Swimming Sea Cucumber <span class="tag-pelagic">Pelagic</span>','','A true abyssopelagic animal! Unlike most sea cucumbers that crawl, this species actively swims through the deep water column.','Sifts fine organic matter (marine snow) from mud when touching down briefly.','Deep-sea fish, larger scavengers.',['Often called the "headless chicken monster" because of its plump, pink, wing-like swimming appendages.','Its body is highly transparent, making its internal digestive tract completely visible.','Spending most of its time swimming allows it to easily relocate and avoid benthic predators.']],
            'arrowworm':['Arrow Worm <span class="tag-pelagic">Pelagic</span>','','Small, highly abundant predators that dart through the water column like tiny glass arrows at almost all depths, including the Abyss.','Copepods, tiny crustaceans, and other zooplankton.','Lanternfish, bristlemouths, jellyfish.',['They are fierce ambush predators that use vibration-sensing hairs to detect prey in total darkness.','Their heads are armed with terrifying, grasping hooks made of chitin to snag their meals.','They are found in massive numbers throughout the ocean, making them a crucial part of the pelagic food web.']]
        };
